ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: FOUNTAIN VALLEY; COUNCIL OKS 3% HIKE IN DEVELOPER FEES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Developer fees have been increased by 3% as the City Council tries to raise 
money to pay for streets and sewer and water lines for new developments. 
</P>
<P>
 The fees hike, which was approved Tuesday, only applies to new residential and 
commercial developments. 
</P>
<P>
 Susan Lynn, environmental programs manager, said that six fees make up the 
developer fees, including those for sewers, annexation to water districts and 
median beautification. 
</P>
<P>
 Lynn said the higher fees will provide revenue to meet the increasing costs of 
improvements. 
</P>
<P>
 The last time developer fees were raised was in the summer of 1991, Lynn said. 
She said fees had not been raised so far during the recession in order to 
promote building in the city. 
</P>
<P>
 How much revenue the new fees will generate depends on the number of projects 
that receive city approval, Lynn said. 
</P>
<P>
 In other action, the council approved spending $71,244 to buy five new police 
vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
 The 1994 Ford Crown Victoria police cars will be bought through an order 
placed by the San Bernardino County Sheriff's Department. DEBRA CANO 
</P>
