<HEADLINE>
<P>
BEACH VOLLEYBALL; KIRBY BEGINS QUEST FOR FIFTH CONSECUTIVE TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IRENE GARCIA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Karolyn Kirby has proved through the years that she is the best player in 
women's pro beach volleyball. 
</P>
<P>
 The 33-year-old has been ranked No. 1 for the last four seasons and has won a 
record 51 tournaments with eight partners. 
</P>
<P>
 At 5 feet 11 she is powerful, quick and consistent. Today in Manhattan Beach, 
Kirby will begin a quest to win her fifth consecutive World Championship title. 
</P>
<P>
 She has won the season-ending event with four partners, including her current 
one, Liz Masakayan, in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 "Karolyn is an exceptional athlete," said Deb Richardson, who is seeded third 
this weekend with partner Dennie Knoop. "That's why she can win with anybody 
and that's why she's at the top." 
</P>
<P>
 Masakayan, a former UCLA All-American, and Kirby have dominated the Women's 
Professional Volleyball Assn. tour for the last two seasons.  
</P>
<P>
 This year they've won 10 of 11 tour events, shutting out most of their 
opponents in the process. And in July, Kirby and Masakayan won the gold medal 
at the Goodwill Games in St. Petersburg, Russia.  
</P>
<P>
 They are seeded No. 1 in the 31-team World Championships, which begin today at 
noon. The final, Sunday at 11 a.m., will be televised live on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
 "This event has always been way physically harder than any other," Kirby said. 
"It's always in August, so it's always hot and it's the end of the season when 
we're tired. Also, the sand is deeper than anywhere in the world." 
</P>
<P>
 Because the third-ranked team of Gail Castro and Elaine Roque will miss the 
championships to compete in an international event in Puerto Rico, the only 
team expected to really challenge Kirby-Masakayan is second-seeded Barbra 
Fontana and Lori Kotas. 
</P>
<P>
 Fontana, a Manhattan Beach native, and Kotas beat Kirby-Masakayan in a 
tournament final in Myrtle Beach, S.C., in late May. 
</P>
<P>
 Last week Masakayan was hospitalized because of a pelvic infection that 
prevented her from training for several days.  
</P>
<P>
 "I have no more aches and pains and my body is completely recovered," she 
said. "But I haven't really been able to work out." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
