<HEADLINE>
<P>
SENSE OF FAMILY LEADS MARCACCINI TO PEPPERDINE; BASKETBALL: AFTER PLAYING IN 
ITALY, SWINGMAN RETURNS TO CALIFORNIA TO BE CLOSE TO AILING FATHER. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANA HADDAD and JEFF FLETCHER, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monte Marcaccini, who spurned Indiana's Bob Knight to play basketball in Italy 
last summer, has returned to California and signed to play college basketball 
at Pepperdine. 
</P>
<P>
 Marcaccini, 19, The Times' Valley player of the year in 1993 while at Notre 
Dame High, said Thursday that the deciding factor was his desire to stay close 
to his ailing father. Giancarlo Marcaccini, 60, is battling lung cancer. 
</P>
<P>
 "I would have loved to go to Indiana," said Marcaccini, a 6-foot-6 swingman. 
"But I have a different situation than I did a year ago, with my dad being 
sick. Our whole family's real close. This is a pretty big blow. It's something 
you've got to deal with." 
</P>
<P>
 His father's illness was diagnosed four months ago. Giancarlo had surgery to 
remove a lung in Paris in June. He continues to live in Paris, where he is 
undergoing radiation treatments. Monte said his father plans to return to 
Encino as soon as he is strong enough. 
</P>
<P>
 "I hope he gets out here as soon as he can," Monte said. 
</P>
<P>
 Marcaccini also was attracted by the new Pepperdine coaching staff, headed by 
former San Diego State Coach Tony Fuller. One of Fuller's assistants is Bob 
Mandeville, who coached lower-level basketball teams at Notre Dame High from 
1986-89. Mandeville also had assisted Fuller with the Aztecs. 
</P>
<P>
 "I know Coach Mandeville," Marcaccini said. "The coaching staff's good guys." 
</P>
<P>
 Marcaccini also has an opportunity to play right away.  
</P>
<P>
 "For my situation, I need to be somewhere where I can play right away and get 
some experience," he said. "Indiana right now probably wouldn't be the best 
place for me to develop my game. Coach Knight's got three guys at my position 
right now. I think I'd be able to play, but not as much as I want." 
</P>
<P>
 In Italy, Marcaccini averaged about 25 points a game as a shooting guard for 
the Benetton United Colors, which won the junior national championship. He led 
Notre Dame to the Southern Section Division III-A championship in 1993, 
averaging 19.7 points and 11.4 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
 He signed with Indiana during the fall signing period in November 1992, 
turning down an offer from UCLA. But last August, Marcaccini left for Italy 
before the start of classes at Indiana. 
</P>
<P>
 Because Marcaccini played for an amateur team in Italy, he retained his NCAA 
eligibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
