<TEXT>
<P>
 Delta-Virgin Atlantic Deal Totters: Four months after Delta Air Lines and 
Virgin Atlantic Airways announced a partnership that would give Delta access to 
London's Heathrow Airport, the two are preparing to abandon linked flights. 
Delta does not have the right to fly passengers there and had hoped to get 
around that by buying blocks of seats on Virgin flights and selling them as 
Delta tickets.The arrangement depended on code sharing, which allows airlines 
to link flights by computer but which also requires U.S. government approval. 
The U.S. Department of Transportation has not given it, blaming Britain's 
refusal to talk seriously about liberalizing air relations. Virgin Atlantic 
said the two airlines intend to proceed with parts of the agreement involving 
merged frequent-flier programs and shared terminal space. 
</P>
